    rationale: "Stage 3 pressure injuries involve full-thickness skin loss with visible subcutaneous adipose tissue. The wound may include undermining or tunneling, but fascia, muscle, tendon, and bone are NOT exposed. Stage 2 involves only partial-thickness loss (dermis exposed or blister). Stage 4 requires exposure of fascia, muscle, tendon, or bone. Unstageable wounds have their base obscured by slough or eschar, preventing accurate staging. The presence of adipose tissue without deeper structure exposure is the defining feature of Stage 3.",
