    selectCount: 2,
    rationale: "Grouped vesicles on an erythematous base are the hallmark of herpes simplex virus (HSV) or varicella-zoster virus (VZV) infection \u2014 the vesicular morphology reflects viral cytopathic effect causing intraepidermal fluid accumulation. Firm, flesh-colored papules with central umbilication are characteristic of molluscum contagiosum, a poxvirus infection. Tense bullae on normal skin suggest autoimmune bullous disease (pemphigoid) or drug reaction, not viral infection. Annular plaques with central clearing suggest dermatophyte infection (tinea) or Lyme disease. Wheals with flare indicate urticaria/allergic reaction.",
    metadata: { topic: "lesion-morphology", priority: "high" },
