    rationale: "The primary anesthesia relevance of psoriatic plaques in the context of regional anesthesia planning is their location relative to planned needle insertion sites. Psoriatic plaques represent areas of disrupted skin barrier \u2014 the epidermis is hyperproliferative, inflamed, and colonized with bacteria. Inserting a needle through a psoriatic plaque introduces bacteria into deeper tissue planes, increasing infection risk. The CRNA must map plaque locations relative to planned IV, peripheral nerve block, or neuraxial access sites and select alternative locations if plaques are present. Pruritus, dermatomal distribution (psoriasis is not dermatomal), and symmetry are less relevant to the immediate procedural planning question.",
    metadata: { topic: "lesion-distribution", priority: "medium" },
