    rationale: "In poorly controlled diabetes, chronic hyperglycemia impairs multiple aspects of wound healing: neutrophil chemotaxis and phagocytosis are reduced (increasing infection risk), keratinocyte and fibroblast proliferation are diminished, and microvascular disease reduces oxygen and nutrient delivery to the wound. These mechanisms collectively extend the already month-long re-epithelialization timeline. Insulin resistance does not accelerate epidermal turnover. Diabetes is associated with impaired, not excessive, collagen synthesis. Hyperglycemia causes osmotic diuresis and does not directly alter plasma oncotic pressure in a way that impairs wound healing.",
